[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The recruitment conversationalist follows the tool-using LLM pattern established in recipes 11.1 through 11.9, with the additions and substitutions specific to clinical-trial recruitment. The architecture is the same shape; the content layers and the governance posture are different.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m At the highest level, the architecture has nine concentric layers around the LLM-and-tools core, plus an offline trial-content authoring pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Layer 1: Channel surface.** Web chat embedded in the institution's research-recruitment portal, in-app messaging in the institution's patient app or in a sponsor-funded recruitment app, SMS through a recruitment short code or 10DLC long code, voice through the institution's research-line IVR, and (where the recruitment plan calls for it) in-person kiosk surfaces at clinical-encounter sites. Each channel has its own session and authentication context, its own consent-capture conventions, and its own per-channel disclosures.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Layer 2: Edge controls.** Rate limiting, bot detection, regional access controls (where the trial's geographic enrollment scope is constrained), and channel-specific compliance gating (TCPA and 10DLC compliance for SMS, voice-recording-disclosure compliance for voice, accessibility conformance for web).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Layer 3: Identity, referral context, and trial context loading.** The patient is identified at the level the recruitment plan requires: in some flows the patient is anonymous-until-prescreen-completes (low-friction entry from sponsor ads), in others the patient is authenticated against the institution's identity provider (when entering from the patient portal), in others the patient enters with a referral token from their treating clinician. Identity establishes which trial (or which trial set) is in scope for the conversation, which IRB-approved content version is active, what consent posture is required for the channel, and what referral context (clinician, sponsor campaign, EHR-prescreen-flag) is attached. Caregiver-or-surrogate identity is captured separately where applicable, with the appropriate proxy-authority documentation per trial type and per state law.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Layer 4: Continuous safety screening.** Every utterance is screened for acute medical emergencies (cardiac, neurological, respiratory, hemorrhagic, anaphylactic, overdose, severe psychiatric crisis), self-harm or suicidal-ideation disclosures, intimate-partner-violence or abuse disclosures, and other crisis events. The recruitment conversation is paused when any of these are detected; the patient is routed to the appropriate emergency or crisis pathway. The screening runs on every input turn, not only the first.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Layer 5: Scope discipline.** Off-scope topics (clinical questions about the patient's existing care, requests for medical advice, requests for diagnosis or treatment recommendations, requests to enroll without prescreen, attempts to push the assistant to recommend the trial) are detected and routed to the appropriate alternative pathway: the patient's existing care team for clinical questions, the institutional patient-services line for general institutional questions, the research-coordinator queue for off-FAQ trial questions, the research-compliance office for compliance concerns, 911 or 988 for safety events.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Layer 6: LLM-and-tool orchestration.** The orchestrator is a tool-using LLM with a per-trial system prompt (parameterized with the IRB-approved recruitment language for the specific trial), strict-grounding retrieval over the IRB-approved trial corpus, deterministic tools for eligibility evaluation and structured-data capture, and audit-grade tool-call logging.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Layer 7: Output safety and faithfulness verification.** Generated responses are verified for citation grounding (every trial-specific assertion traces to an IRB-approved source), for IRB-approved-language compliance (no novel recruitment language), for scope compliance (no diagnosis, no recommendation, no out-of-FAQ content), for eligibility-determination posture (preliminary, not final), and for required-disclosure presence (the mandated IRB disclosures appear in every conversation). Failures regenerate or fall back to a safe response.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Layer 8: Coordinator-handoff orchestration and downstream operational workflows.** Qualified handoffs are routed to the coordinator queue with a structured prescreen summary attached. Closed or paused trials route to alternative-trial-discovery flows (where institutional policy permits) or to thank-you-and-resources flows (where it does not). Disqualified prospects are thanked and (where the institution has a referral-to-other-trials capability) offered the alternative-recruitment pathway. Demographic representativeness data is captured per the IRB-approved data-collection plan.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Layer 9: Audit, retention, IRB-grade reporting, and cohort-level monitoring.** Every conversation is captured in a durable record with model versions, prompt versions, IRB-approved-content versions, eligibility-rule versions, prescreen-result, handoff disposition, and demographic context. Per-cohort funnel monitoring (entry to prescreen-completion to coordinator-handoff to consent to randomize) is reviewed by the principal investigator, the institutional research-recruitment team, the sponsor's recruitment team, and (for FDA-regulated trials with diversity-action-plan requirements) the diversity-tracking team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Offline: trial-content authoring and IRB-review pipeline.** Trial-specific content (protocol summary, eligibility criteria, FAQ, visit-schedule, study-procedure summary, recruitment-language assets) is authored by the institutional research-recruitment team in collaboration with the principal investigator, the sponsor's recruitment team, and (where applicable) patient-advocate consultants. The content goes through IRB review. Approved content is version-controlled, signed-off by named clinical-leadership owners, and deployed to the assistant's grounded-retrieval index as a versioned snapshot. Amendments follow the same pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The data flows in the recruitment context are:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Inbound conversation:** patient utterance plus channel and identity context plus referral context flows from channel through edge controls and identity to the orchestration core.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Outbound recruitment information:** IRB-approved trial content flows from the grounded retrieval index through the LLM (in retrieval-and-citation mode, not generation-from-scratch mode) through output safety to the patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Eligibility evaluation:** patient-reported information plus structured criteria flow through the deterministic eligibility-evaluation tool back to the orchestrator with a structured result.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Prescreen capture:** structured patient-reported data flows from the orchestrator to the prescreen-store with provenance, timestamps, and consent context preserved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Coordinator handoff:** the structured prescreen summary, the patient's stated questions, the patient's preferred follow-up channel and time, and the conversation context flow from the orchestrator to the coordinator queue with the handoff arrangement confirmed back to the patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Audit and reporting:** model and prompt versions, retrieval citations, tool calls, eligibility-rule outputs, IRB-approved-content versions, prescreen-result, handoff disposition, and demographic context flow from the orchestrator to the audit pipeline and to the per-cohort dashboards.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shape is consistent with the rest of chapter 11. The trial-specific differences are the IRB-approved-content corpus as the only allowed source of trial language, the per-trial isolation of context, the deterministic eligibility-evaluation engine with named clinical-leadership ownership, the coordinator-handoff orchestration as production scope, the trial-state and amendment tracking, the representativeness instrumentation, the vulnerable-populations-aware identity model, and the research-data-as-distinct-record-class retention posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
