[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Bedrock for the LLM and embeddings.** Same selection criteria as recipes 11.1 through 11.9. The recruitment conversationalist specifically benefits from a model with strong instruction-following for IRB-approved-language compliance, strong retrieval-grounding behavior so the model surfaces approved content rather than improvising trial language, strong tool-use for the eligibility-evaluation and prescreen-capture tools, and good multilingual support to reach the patient populations the trial is trying to enroll. Claude Sonnet-class models or comparable frontier models for the orchestration layer; smaller models for intent classification, FAQ-routing pre-filtering, and conversation-state summarization. Bedrock provides HIPAA-eligible deployment under BAA. The recruitment context places a heavy premium on grounded-retrieval discipline; the architecture treats the LLM as a retrieval-and-citation engine for trial content, not as a generation engine for novel recruitment language.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Bases for the per-trial IRB-approved corpus.** Each trial has an IRB-approved corpus including the protocol summary in IRB-approved language, the eligibility-criteria description in IRB-approved language, the recruitment FAQ entries in IRB-approved language, the visit-schedule summary, the study-procedure summary, the recruitment-language assets across approved channels, and the IRB and protocol identifiers. Knowledge Bases provides the managed RAG layer with metadata-filtered retrieval (trial_id, content_type, language, reading_level, IRB-approval-version, effective-date). Per-trial isolation is enforced through the trial_id metadata filter; queries from a conversation about trial A cannot retrieve content from trial B.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Bedrock Agents for tool orchestration.** The assistant's tools (trial_state_retrieve, trial_content_retrieve, faq_retrieve, eligibility_evaluate, prescreen_capture, coordinator_handoff_schedule, alternative_trial_search, escalation_propose, demographic_capture, conversation_audit) are defined as Agents action groups with OpenAPI schemas. The Agent's traces preserve tool-call audit trails as part of the IRB-grade conversation record.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Bedrock Guardrails for scope and content filtering.** Configured with denied topics including diagnosis-attempted, treatment-recommendation-attempted, prescription-attempted, trial-recommendation-attempted (the assistant explains; it does not recommend), comparison-of-trials-as-recommendation, informed-consent-attempted (consent is a separate, regulated process the assistant does not run), and similar scope violations. The recruitment context's scope discipline is broader than for the symptom-checker triage bot in some directions and narrower in others; the configuration reflects the specific scope of recruitment-conversation work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon OpenSearch Serverless for the retrieval indices.** The per-trial IRB-approved corpus, the institutional research-recruitment FAQ corpus, the patient-education library (where the recruitment plan includes general education content), and the conversation-history retrieval index all benefit from vector retrieval with metadata filtering.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for per-trial state, prescreen capture, conversation state, coordinator-handoff queue, and audit journals.** Multiple tables supporting the recruitment lifecycle: `trial-registry` (per-trial active/closed/paused state, IRB-amendment status, site enrollment status, recruitment-pause status), `trial-content-version-registry` (per-trial active IRB-approved-content version with effective dates), `eligibility-rule-registry` (per-trial deterministic eligibility-rule definitions with version history and named clinical-leadership ownership), `prescreen-store` (per-prospect structured prescreen data with provenance), `conversation-state` (per-conversation transient state), `conversation-metadata` (per-conversation turn-by-turn data with citation chains), `tool-call-ledger` (audited tool invocations), `coordinator-handoff-queue` (qualified handoffs awaiting coordinator pickup), `recruitment-decision-record-journal` (durable record of recruitment-conversation outcomes with citations), `consent-and-disclosure-record` (per-conversation IRB-disclosure-acknowledgement and data-collection-consent record), `representativeness-instrumentation-store` (per-cohort funnel data per the IRB-approved data-collection plan).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for the IRB-approved corpus archive, conversation archive, recruitment-decision-record journal, and per-trial regulatory-artifact archive.** Object Lock in compliance mode for the retention window, with retention sized to the longest of HIPAA's six-year minimum, the trial's specific IRB-mandated retention (often the longer of life-of-trial-plus-six-years or the sponsor's contractual retention), state-specific medical-record retention rules, and FDA-IND or FDA-IDE record-retention obligations where applicable. Per-trial S3 prefixes with per-trial KMS-key separation provide blast-radius containment between trials.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for the conversation handler, ingestion adapters, eligibility-evaluation tool, prescreen-capture tool, coordinator-handoff tool, alternative-trial-search tool, escalation tool, demographic-capture tool, IRB-grade audit pipeline, and per-cohort reporting.** Same Lambda-as-glue pattern as the previous chapter 11 recipes, with additional Lambdas for each major tool and for the recruitment-funnel reporting workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon API Gateway and AWS WAF for the public chat endpoint.** Same as the other recipes, with rate-limiting and bot-detection rules tuned for sponsor-funded recruitment campaigns where ad-driven traffic spikes are routine.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Connect for warm-handoff to research coordinators.** When the assistant qualifies a prospect and the prospect prefers a real-time handoff (rather than a scheduled callback), Connect routes to the institutional research-coordinator queue with the prescreen summary and conversation context attached. Coordinators are reachable via Connect's chat and voice queues.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Pinpoint for scheduled coordinator-callback messaging and recruitment-campaign communication.** Confirmation messages, callback reminders, and (where the recruitment plan includes proactive outreach) invitation messages to EHR-flagged prospects are delivered via Pinpoint with delivery-status tracking, channel-preference enforcement, and quiet-hours discipline. TCPA and 10DLC compliance for SMS is operationalized at this layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon EventBridge for the recruitment-event bus.** Events including conversation_started, prescreen_completed, eligibility_determined, coordinator_handoff_scheduled, coordinator_handoff_accepted, coordinator_handoff_aged_out, alternative_trial_offered, conversation_closed, IRB_amendment_applied, trial_paused, trial_closed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Step Functions for trial-onboarding and IRB-amendment-deployment workflows.** Each new trial onboarding (content authoring, IRB review, eligibility-rule encoding, FAQ population, coordinator-team training, post-launch monitoring activation) and each IRB-approved amendment runs as a Step Functions workflow with named ownership at each step.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS HealthLake (optional) for chart-context retrieval where the trial's recruitment plan includes EHR-prescreen-flag pathways.** Where the institution operates an EHR-driven prescreen-flag program (the EHR identifies potentially-eligible patients and the recruitment platform invites them to learn more), HealthLake provides the FHIR-native chart-context the assistant references during the prescreen conversation. The assistant does not access chart data without the patient's IRB-approved consent for that data use.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Comprehend Medical (optional) for medical-named-entity recognition over patient-reported text.** When the patient reports a medication name, a condition, a lab value, or a clinician name in conversation, Comprehend Medical can extract structured terms for matching against the eligibility-evaluation tool's input schema.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS KMS, AWS Secrets Manager, Amazon CloudWatch, AWS CloudTrail, Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose, AWS Glue, Amazon Athena.** Same operational and audit primitives as the previous recipes, with recruitment-specific KMS-key separation per trial for blast-radius containment, separate keys for the recruitment-decision-record journal, and separate keys for the representativeness-instrumentation store.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon QuickSight for per-trial recruitment-funnel and representativeness dashboards.** Per-trial dashboards (entry-volume, prescreen-completion rate, qualified-handoff rate, coordinator-handoff-accept rate, consent rate, randomization rate) with per-cohort slices (language, race and ethnicity, sex and gender, age cohort, geography, insurance status, social-determinants flags, referral source) reviewed by the principal investigator, the institutional research-recruitment team, the sponsor's recruitment team, and the diversity-tracking team for FDA-regulated trials.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker (optional) for custom eligibility-evaluation classifiers where deterministic rules are insufficient.** Some eligibility criteria are difficult to evaluate purely deterministically (e.g., "patient has clinically-significant comorbid depression"); calibrated classifiers with named clinical-leadership ownership and IRB-reviewed validation evidence may augment the deterministic engine where the IRB has approved their use.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
