[49m[38;5;10m+    498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    499[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    500[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    501[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    502[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Bedrock (Agents, Knowledge Bases, Guardrails, foundation model with strong tool-use and instruction-following, embedding model), Amazon OpenSearch Serverless, AWS Lambda, AWS Step Functions, Amazon API Gateway, AWS WAF, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon S3, AWS KMS (with separate keys per trial and for the recruitment-decision-record store and the representativeness-instrumentation store), AWS Secrets Manager, Amazon CloudWatch, AWS CloudTrail, Amazon EventBridge, Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose, AWS Glue, Amazon Athena, Amazon Pinpoint, Amazon Connect (warm handoff to research coordinators), Amazon QuickSight (per-trial recruitment-funnel and representativeness dashboards). Optionally: AWS HealthLake (chart-context retrieval where the recruitment plan includes EHR-prescreen-flag pathways), Amazon Comprehend Medical (NER over patient-reported text), Amazon SageMaker (custom eligibility-evaluation classifiers where IRB-approved). |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    503[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **External Inputs** | Per-trial IRB-approved corpus (protocol summary, eligibility-criteria description, recruitment FAQ, visit-schedule summary, study-procedure summary, recruitment-language assets) authored by the institutional research-recruitment team in collaboration with the principal investigator and the sponsor, reviewed and approved by the IRB, version-controlled with named clinical-leadership ownership. Per-trial deterministic eligibility-rule library encoded by clinical informatics in collaboration with clinical leadership and the sponsor's clinical operations team, with named per-rule ownership and IRB-review evidence. Per-trial recruitment plan including target-cohort definitions and diversity-action-plan targets where applicable. Coordinator-team capacity and queue-management infrastructure. ClinicalTrials.gov listing per FDAAA 801 and NIH policies. Sponsor-side recruitment-tracking integration where the sponsor's contractual requirements include it. EHR-prescreen-flag program where the institution operates one. Patient-advocate consultant input on recruitment-language tone and on the equity-and-trust posture for affected populations. Multilingual translations of patient-facing content with native-speaker review and IRB sign-off per trial-language combination. <!-- TODO: verify; specific external inputs vary by institution and per trial; the IRB-approved-corpus authoring is the largest pre-deployment investment per trial --> |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    504[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | Per-Lambda least-privilege roles. The trial-content-loading Lambda has read access to the per-trial Knowledge Base. The eligibility-evaluation Lambda has read access to the eligibility-rule registry and (where used) invoke permission on the SageMaker eligibility-classifier endpoint. The prescreen-capture Lambda has write access to the prescreen store with provenance-stamping. The coordinator-handoff Lambda has write access to the coordinator-handoff queue and invoke permission on the Connect routing. The audit Lambda has write access to the recruitment-decision-record journal. Resource-based policies pin invoking principals to the production Bedrock Agent action-group ARNs and the production API Gateway stage ARN. Per-trial KMS-key access is scoped to the Lambdas operating on that trial's content; cross-trial access is denied at the IAM layer. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    505[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA and Compliance** | AWS BAA signed. Verify all services in scope are HIPAA-eligible at build time. The assistant is patient-facing PHI in a research context; HIPAA's research provisions, 45 CFR 46 (the Common Rule), 21 CFR Part 50 (informed consent for FDA-regulated research), 21 CFR Part 56 (IRBs), and ICH-GCP guidelines apply. <!-- TODO: verify; the regulatory landscape for clinical-trial recruitment software includes HIPAA, the Common Rule (45 CFR 46), FDA 21 CFR Parts 50 and 56, ICH E6 GCP guidelines, FDA guidance on diversity action plans, FDA guidance on decentralized trials, state-specific clinical-trial regulations where applicable, and (for international sites) regional frameworks such as EU CTR and MHRA --> The institutional regulatory team reviews the recruitment-platform regulatory posture before launch and on each material scope change. The institutional IRB reviews the recruitment-script content, the prescreen flow, the FAQ content, the routing logic, the data-collection plan, and the eligibility-evaluation logic. Vulnerable-populations protections (45 CFR 46 Subparts B, C, D for pregnant women, prisoners, and children) apply where the trial enrolls those populations. Consent for research is governed by 21 CFR Part 50 and the IRB-approved consent procedure; the assistant does not run consent. State-specific provisions on AI-mediated patient-recruitment communication may apply. The sponsor's regulatory and clinical-operations teams are involved for sponsor-funded trials. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | Per-trial IRB-approved corpus, conversation archive, recruitment-decision-record journal, regulatory-artifact archive: SSE-KMS with per-trial customer-managed keys for blast-radius containment between trials. Recruitment-decision-record journal: SSE-KMS with separately-managed customer key. Representativeness-instrumentation store: SSE-KMS with separately-managed customer key (representativeness data is sensitive and access-controlled separately). S3 archives: Object Lock in compliance mode for the retention window. DynamoDB tables: customer-managed KMS at rest, with sensitive tables on separate keys. Lambda environment variables: KMS-encrypted. Secrets Manager: customer-managed KMS. TLS in transit for all AWS API calls and all integrations with external systems including ClinicalTrials.gov, sponsor-side recruitment-tracking systems, and (where used) HealthLake or other FHIR endpoints. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: tool Lambdas, ingestion Lambdas, audit pipeline, and integrations with sponsor-side and EHR-side systems run in VPC with controlled egress. PrivateLink to vendor-hosted endpoints where supported; tightly-scoped NAT path with allow-list otherwise. VPC endpoints for DynamoDB, S3, KMS, Secrets Manager, CloudWatch Logs, EventBridge, Bedrock, OpenSearch Serverless, Step Functions, Pinpoint, Connect, Comprehend Medical, HealthLake, and SageMaker (where used). The patient-facing edge is public; the back-office and sponsor-side and EHR-side integration traffic is private. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled with data events on all sensitive S3 buckets (per-trial IRB-approved corpus, audit archive, recruitment-decision-record journal, regulatory-artifact archive) and DynamoDB tables (trial registry, trial-content-version registry, eligibility-rule registry, prescreen store, conversation state, conversation metadata, tool-call ledger, coordinator-handoff queue, recruitment-decision-record journal, consent and disclosure record, representativeness instrumentation), Secrets Manager secrets, and customer-managed KMS keys. Bedrock and Bedrock Agents invocations logged. Lambda invocations logged. API Gateway access logs enabled. Step Functions execution logs enabled. Connect interactions logged with appropriate retention. Pinpoint message-status logs preserved. CloudTrail logs in a dedicated S3 bucket with Object Lock in compliance mode. Audit retention sized to the longest of HIPAA's six-year minimum, the trial's IRB-mandated retention (often longer), state-specific medical-record retention rules, FDA-IND or FDA-IDE record-retention obligations where applicable, and litigation-hold obligations. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    509[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic prospective-participant profiles stratified by trial type (phase 1 oncology, phase 4 primary-care, healthy-volunteer, decentralized, site-based, pediatric, vulnerable-population), by language, by referral source (clinician referral, sponsor ad, ClinicalTrials.gov entry, EHR-prescreen-flag, institutional landing page), by demographic stratum (per the IRB-approved data-collection plan), by eligibility profile (clearly-eligible, clearly-disqualified, uncertain-pending). Synthetic per-trial IRB-approved corpora reviewed by clinical leadership for representative therapeutic-area coverage. Synthetic per-trial deterministic eligibility-rule libraries with named ownership. Synthetic conversation histories covering qualified-handoff, screen-failure, patient-declined, alternative-trial-offered, and emergency-routed scenarios. Test research-coordinator queues with synthetic coordinator capacity profiles. Test EHR FHIR endpoints, sponsor-side recruitment-tracking endpoints, and ClinicalTrials.gov listing data with synthetic content. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    510[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | At an institutional research-recruitment platform scale serving 30 to 200 active trials with aggregate prospective-participant traffic of approximately 50,000 to 500,000 conversations per year (varying widely with the trial portfolio's recruitment plans and sponsor-funded campaign volume): Bedrock LLM invocations typically $0.50-2.00 per recruitment conversation (orchestration model plus tool-call overhead), totaling approximately $25,000-1,000,000 per year. Bedrock Agents and Knowledge Bases hosting plus the OpenSearch Serverless retrieval indices typically $40,000-250,000 per year (varies with the active trial count and per-trial corpus size). Lambda, API Gateway, WAF, DynamoDB, S3, KMS, Secrets Manager, CloudWatch, CloudTrail, EventBridge, Kinesis Firehose, Glue, Athena, Step Functions total approximately $60,000-300,000 per year. Connect typically $30,000-200,000 per year (varies with warm-handoff volume). Pinpoint typically $10,000-80,000 per year. Comprehend Medical (where used) typically $10,000-60,000 per year. HealthLake (where used) typically $30,000-150,000 per year. SageMaker (where used) typically $15,000-60,000 per year. Total AWS infrastructure typically $200,000-2,000,000 per year at this scale. Per-qualified-prescreen infrastructure cost typically falls in the $8-25 range, varying widely with trial complexity, channel mix, model choice, eligibility-criteria depth, and coordinator-handoff volume. The institutional research-recruitment workforce cost (research coordinators, recruitment-program managers, IRB-staff, regulatory operations, content authoring) is typically larger than the AWS infrastructure cost and is the dominant operational expense; deployments that under-invest in coordinator capacity and content-authoring workforce are deployments with patient-experience and regulatory-quality gaps. <!-- TODO: replace with verified pricing once the implementing team validates against the AWS Pricing Calculator; specific costs depend on Bedrock model choice, recruitment-conversation volume, active-trial count, channel mix, and integration depth --> |
