[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks (illustrative, your mileage varies):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Old recruitment funnel (tear-off ad to coordinator phone screen) | Recruitment conversationalist with coordinator handoff |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|-----------------------------------------|----------------------------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Time-to-first-coordinator-conversation (median) | 1-3 weeks from patient interest to coordinator pickup | 24-72 hours from patient interest to coordinator pickup |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Patient time invested in prescreen | 30-60 minutes of phone-tag plus 30-45 minutes of coordinator phone screen | 8-20 minutes of conversation |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Prescreen-completion rate | Variable; often low for forms; moderate for phone screens | 50-70% of patients who start the conversation complete the prescreen |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Qualified-handoff rate (of prescreens completed) | Variable by trial | 30-55% across the institutional trial portfolio (varies widely by trial complexity) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Coordinator-time-saved per qualified prospect | Baseline | 25-40 minutes of coordinator phone-screen time per qualified handoff |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Per-conversation infrastructure cost | Negligible for static ad; coordinator time at $40-100 per hour for the screen | $0.50-2.00 per conversation |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Per-qualified-prescreen total cost (infrastructure plus coordinator-time-saved) | High (coordinator time dominant) | $8-25 per qualified prescreen |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Citation-coverage rate (fraction of trial-specific assertions grounded in IRB-approved corpus) | N/A (coordinator's verbal coverage was the standard) | 95%+ as launch-gate target |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Demographic representativeness in qualified handoffs | Often skewed toward established institutional patients | Monitored per cohort with explicit equity targets |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | IRB-grade audit reproducibility | Partial (handwritten coordinator notes) | Complete (versioned content, versioned rules, versioned prompts, version-stamped on every recruitment-decision record) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO: replace illustrative figures with measured results from the deployment. The ranges above are typical for hybrid AI-plus-coordinator recruitment programs but vary substantially with trial type, therapeutic area, recruitment-plan design, and the institution's coordinator workforce capacity. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Trials with deep clinical-judgment criteria.** When a substantial fraction of eligibility criteria require clinical-judgment evaluation (severity, prognosis, comorbidity context), the assistant's deterministic engine flags many criteria for coordinator review and the prescreen-yield improvement is bounded. Mitigation: per-trial calibration of the eligibility-evaluation engine; classifier-augmented evaluation (with IRB review) for criteria where clinical-judgment patterns can be encoded; honest expectation-setting that not every trial benefits equally from this pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Patients with complex medical histories the prescreen cannot capture.** A patient with multiple comorbidities, multiple medications, multiple prior treatments, and multiple historical lab values may not be able to provide the depth the prescreen needs in a single session. Mitigation: chart-context-pull where the IRB-approved consent permits; multi-session prescreen where the trial allows; explicit handoff with "coordinator will work with you on the rest."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Prospective participants from populations with low digital-tool engagement.** The patients with the greatest unmet research-participation opportunity are often the patients with the most limited digital-tool access. Mitigation: deliberate channel diversification (SMS, voice, in-person kiosk options at clinical-encounter sites), partnerships with community-based organizations, multilingual content, and explicit equity instrumentation with named clinical-leadership ownership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recruitment for vulnerable populations.** Pediatric, prisoner-population, pregnant-women-specific, and cognitively-impaired-population trials require additional protections under 45 CFR 46 Subparts B, C, and D. Mitigation: specific identity-and-consent flows per protected population; specific architectural extensions per the institutional protocol; explicit IRB review of the population-specific recruitment platform configuration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Mid-conversation IRB amendments.** A trial whose protocol amends mid-recruitment may require updated information delivered to in-flight prospective participants. Mitigation: amendment-deployment workflow that detects in-flight conversations affected by the amendment and, per the IRB-approved amendment process, re-presents the relevant updated information.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Patients in distress during the conversation.** Patients facing serious illness, recent diagnoses, or progressive disease may surface emotional distress mid-conversation. Mitigation: continuous safety screening; warm acknowledgement language reviewed by patient-advocate consultants; routing to the institutional patient-services line or to mental-health-support resources where the patient indicates they would like one; the assistant does not provide counseling.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Mistrust of clinical research disclosed mid-conversation.** Patients from populations with documented historical reasons to mistrust clinical research may surface concerns mid-conversation. Mitigation: IRB-approved language reviewed with patient-advocate consultants and (where applicable) the institution's community-research-engagement teams; explicit acknowledgement; routing to the coordinator for in-depth conversation rather than the assistant attempting to resolve in-conversation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Sponsor-funded recruitment campaigns with traffic spikes.** Sponsor ads or social-media campaigns can produce sudden traffic that exceeds coordinator-team capacity. Mitigation: smooth-flow throttling rather than burst-and-wait dynamics; sponsor-side communication of expected coordinator capacity; pre-campaign capacity sizing with the sponsor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Multi-trial scenarios where the patient is plausibly a candidate for more than one.** The assistant has to discuss one trial at a time and avoid framings that compare trials as recommendations. Mitigation: explicit institutional policy on multi-trial scenarios; the assistant offers information about other trials only when the patient asks and only with IRB-approved language for each.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Cross-language asset gaps.** Validated translations of per-trial IRB-approved content are difficult to maintain at scale. Mitigation: per-trial-language-combination IRB review; native-speaker review; explicit per-language launch gates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Coordinator capacity saturation.** A platform that delivers more qualified handoffs than the coordinator team can absorb produces patient-experience problems and trial-operations problems. Mitigation: capacity-aware throttling; coordinator-team workforce planning as part of the recruitment-platform capacity plan; honest expectation-setting with the trial sponsor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Outcome-correlation lag.** The platform's effect on consented and randomized enrollments accumulates across the trial's enrollment period; per-trial validation in a single quarter is rarely possible. Mitigation: portfolio-level reporting across the institution's active trial set; explicit acknowledgement of the time-horizon mismatch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Per-cohort demographic-disparity signals.** Per-cohort monitoring may reveal that the platform's handoff-yield differs by demographic stratum in ways that do not reflect underlying clinical reality. Mitigation: per-cohort monitoring as launch-gate; periodic clinical-quality review with explicit equity focus; recruitment-plan-revision process incorporating equity findings.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Adversarial inputs.** Patients (or others) attempting prompt injection to extract protocol-confidential information, manipulate eligibility evaluation, or test the system. Mitigation: input-safety pipeline with prompt-injection detection; output-safety pipeline with citation-coverage verification and IRB-approved-language compliance verification; per-trial jailbreak-test corpus.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Requests to enroll without prescreen or to commit to participation in conversation.** Patients sometimes try to skip the prescreen or to commit to participation before consent. Mitigation: scope-violation screening; explicit IRB-approved language explaining the prescreen-and-consent sequence; routing to coordinator for any out-of-flow request.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Why This Isn't Production-Ready
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pseudocode and architecture above demonstrate the pattern. A production deployment needs to close several gaps that are intentionally out of scope for a recipe.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-trial IRB-approved content authoring with full institutional governance.** The single largest pre-deployment investment per trial is authoring the IRB-approved content, encoding the eligibility-rule library with named clinical-leadership ownership, populating the FAQ corpus, and getting the IRB sign-off. Each artifact has an effective date, a named owner, and an annual review schedule. The content is rebuilt or incrementally updated when the protocol amends. Each retrieval chunk is tagged with trial_id, content_version, content_type, language, and reading_level. The IRB's signature is the launch gate; trials cannot go into production without it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-trial deterministic eligibility-rule library with named per-rule ownership.** Each criterion is encoded with named clinical-leadership ownership, version history, IRB-review evidence, and per-rule documentation describing what the rule evaluates and how it should be interpreted. Below-threshold rule libraries (incomplete, ambiguous, or unowned) are not approved for launch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA-strategy artifact with regulatory-counsel review.** Patient-facing recruitment software is part of the trial's regulatory artifact. The institutional regulatory positioning is documented, reviewed by FDA-experienced regulatory counsel for FDA-regulated trials, and maintained as the deployment evolves. For trials with sponsor-side regulatory teams, the sponsor's regulatory team is part of the review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Continuous-emergency-screening pipeline with formal validation.** The screening layer is validated against a held-out corpus of emergency-presentation cases (curated and reviewed by clinical leadership) before launch and on each material update. False-negative rate is the launch-gate metric.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Citation-grounding discipline as architectural floor.** Every trial-specific assertion is grounded in a cited IRB-approved-content source with the version preserved. The citation-coverage-rate metric is a launch-gate threshold.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IRB-approved-language compliance verification on every output.** A faithfulness-check stage between Bedrock generation and response delivery ensures the output contains only IRB-approved trial language and the IRB-mandated disclosures, regenerates or falls back to safe response on failure, and logs cross-check outcomes for audit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-trial isolation enforcement.** Cross-trial content leakage (content from trial A surfacing in a conversation about trial B) is a regulatory finding and an operational defect. Per-trial Knowledge-Base metadata filtering, per-trial KMS-key isolation, per-trial IAM scoping, and per-trial audit trails enforce the isolation defense-in-depth.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordinator-team workflow integration.** The coordinator handoff is a first-class capability with a comprehensive payload schema. The coordinator team's workflow is co-designed; deploying without coordinator-team involvement produces an assistant the coordinator team does not use. Per-coordinator-queue capacity awareness is built into the platform.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-cohort representativeness monitoring with launch-gate discipline.** Per-trial recruitment funnel by language, race and ethnicity (per OMB self-report), sex assigned at birth, gender identity, age cohort, geography, insurance status, social-determinants flags, and referral source. Per-cohort dashboards reviewed by the principal investigator, the institutional research-recruitment team, the sponsor's recruitment team, and the diversity-tracking team for FDA-regulated trials.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome-tracking pipeline through to consent and randomization.** The platform's effect on consented and randomized enrollments is the substantive outcome metric, and accumulating it requires data integration with the institution's clinical-trial management system (CTMS) and the sponsor's randomization tracking. Operational ownership is jointly held by the principal investigator, the institutional research-recruitment team, and the sponsor's recruitment team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Mid-conversation IRB-amendment-deployment workflow.** The amendment-deployment workflow detects in-flight conversations affected by the amendment and, per the IRB-approved amendment process, re-presents the relevant updated information. Operational tested in tabletop drills with the IRB before each material amendment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-language deployment with validated translations.** Per-trial-language-combination IRB review. Native-speaker review of every patient-facing language asset. Per-language launch-gate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Vulnerable-populations-aware identity model.** Pediatric, surrogate-decision-maker, pregnant-women, prisoner-population, and other protected-population scenarios require additional architectural extensions per the institutional protocol and per the trial's specific 45 CFR 46 Subpart-applicable protections. The architecture is designed for the adult-baseline pattern and is extended for protected populations as the institutional protocol requires.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Disaster-recovery topology.** When the per-trial Knowledge Base, the eligibility-rule registry, the coordinator-queue routing, or any downstream integration is unreachable, the platform degrades gracefully. Per-source failover behavior is documented and tested quarterly. Cross-region failover for Bedrock and the institutional integrations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Compensation operations for incorrect or disputed handoffs.** When a coordinator or a sponsor disputes a handoff (the prescreen included incorrect data; the eligibility evaluation surfaced an erroneous result; the IRB-approved language was misused), the operations team reproduces the conversation, retrieves the cited content and rule versions, and either confirms the platform followed the IRB-approved process or confirms the platform deviated and feeds the failure mode into the improvement loop. Tooling for this workflow is part of production scope.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational ownership across multiple teams.** The platform sits at the intersection of the institutional research-recruitment team, the IRB, regulatory affairs, the principal investigator and clinical-trials staff, IT, the coordinator workforce, the sponsor's recruitment and clinical-operations teams, and (for FDA-regulated trials) the FDA-strategy-artifact owner. Establish clear ownership at the start.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy rigor.** Several mature commercial vendors offer recruitment platforms with FAQ-bot, eligibility-prescreen, and coordinator-handoff capabilities. Most major institutions running sizable trial portfolios run a hybrid: build a thin orchestration layer in-house on the institution's preferred infrastructure, partner with vendors for specific trial-recruitment campaigns where vendor capability is strong, and integrate with the institution's research-recruitment, IRB, and coordinator workflows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[K
